ed, 3 Apr 1996, Michael Meissner wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; I rev'ed up to Linux 1.3.79 and then 1.3.81, and found that readline<br />&gt; won't build.  I then rev'ed up to the latest beta libc (5.3.8) and<br />&gt; termcap (2.0.6), and the error was still there.  The reason is it<br />&gt; includes termcap.h, which has the following lines:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; 	#include &lt;features.h&gt;<br />&gt; 	#include &lt;sys/types.h&gt;<br />&gt; <br />&gt; 	extern char PC;<br />&gt; 	extern char *UP;<br />&gt; 	extern char *BC;<br />&gt; <br />&gt; 	#ifdef __linux__<br />&gt; 	extern speed_t ospeed;<br />&gt; 	#else<br />&gt; 	extern short ospeed;<br />&gt; 	#endif<br /><br />Mmm.. I _think_ that it should include &lt;termios.h&gt;, according to POSIX. <br />That's where speed_t should be (but I don't have the POSIX stuff here: <br />it's at the university). So the correct fix would be to just include that <br />in termcap.h, and then it should work with all kernels.<br /><br />The #ifdef __linux__ looks a bit suspicious too. speed_t isn't any linux <br />specific thing, it's quite standard.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
